E ignorance knowledge~
Excerpt from the analysis of "In Order to Learn" by Veszhas Meldaeus, its      
publishing in 99 SB marked the beginning of the renaissence of the Scions,     
entitled "Of Knowledge and Ignorance."     
     
   "As the Great Kreousili wrote before me, ignorance is a plague that has infected     
the masses, and a difficult one to cure. Our predecessors enlightened themselves,     
but failed to make an impact on the world and the sickness that we call ignorance.     
It is a necessity that we right this wrong by giving this ancient cause a second     
attempt.     
     
   "Quoting my beloved and ancient mentor, "...Those who do not accept knowledge do not     
accept life." Kreousili saw then in his wisdom what few are able to see now: those     
that are ignorant are not worthy of the gift of life. Ignorance is life without     
living. The enlightened must cure this ignorance by any means possible. It is to     
be remembered that those who are incapable of understanding and creativity are     
not to be allowed to live; their ignorance cannot be cured but only spread. What     
we must do is burn them until they are but dust so that no remainants of their     
foolishness can be found.     
     
   "This hour the Scions of Knowledge are reborn, and our cause has become clearer     
than ever. Let the dark ages end and the new ages begin through use of our precious     
tools of knowledge and creativity! The best of the old renewed through use of     
the innovations of the new, we shall see our golden age."     
~
E order learn~
An excerpt from the work "In Order to Learn" by Kreousili, Founder of the     
original Scions of Knowledge, 1520 AB.     
     
   "In order to more clearly define what knowledge is, a wise man must first     
attempt to discover the nature of ignorance. Ignorance is far more than     
the lack of knowledge, just as knowledge is far more than a scab to cover     
ignorance.     
     
   "It has been said that knowledge is power. If this is true, then the     
relationship between knowledge and ignorance is not unlike a watermill that     
generates power. A man who does not know is a dry watermill; he may have a     
revelation. A man who does not want to know is a watermill built far from a     
river. It will take much to convince him of his ignorance. A man that believes     
he knows is a watermill built atop a mountain, for he places himself far above     
the aspirations of knowledge. This is the most dangerous type of ignorance, and     
the most difficult to cure.     
     
   "A necessary component of life is learning, and those who do not accept knowledge     
do not accept life. One may be unlearned yet not be considered ignorant, as his      
mind is still opened and free just as one can be learned and ignorant by not     
being able to generalize and interpret the knowledge wasted upon him. A head      
full of knowledge may still be locked; its only key is creativity. Creativity      
is what allows new knowledge to be discovered, and old knowledge to become      
renewed.     
     
   "Using the dual tools of knowledge and creativity allows the wielder to     
extrapolate information and apply it to situations that one will find himself     
in over the course of a life. One who walks the path of knowledge knows and      
recognizes what can be done in a situation, and never wastes so much as a breath     
on what is futile. There is but one reality, but no two perceptions are alike.      
It is important for one to concentrate on the reality in addition to his      
perceptions to avoid ignorance, for ignorance is the state of being oblivious     
to the world around himself, and can spread among the masses as a plague..."     
~
E history glass tower~
"The History of the Glass Tower"     
An excerpt from "The Beginnings of Aetullan"     
- Scribed in 368 SB by Dalgrivos Mel'nur, First Historian of Aetullan     
  Translated into common in 906 SB by Celirell Derechum     
     
   Our beloved yet feared monolith of glass which has been far before the     
recollection of the eldest of elves, or their fathers. It was of the few     
structures to survive the Great War, and the means by which it was crafted     
continues to confound the most masterful carpenters and artisians. So I     
attempt here, in these pages, to answer the question that has been asked     
by so many: From where does the Glass Tower come, and what is the reason     
for its existence?     
     
It is known that the Tower existed long before the Great War. The glass     
shows no scratch nor does it show any mark, so that by simply viewing it     
with one's own eyes one cannot glean any knowledge about its age. The     
Tower's walls flow with magic that is powerful, subtle and likely to not     
be understood in full for generations upon generations, if it all. It is     
also believed that the Tower is crafted out of a single piece of glass.     
     
The glass itself is not normal in any sense. The precision in which it     
has been molded or cut or otherwise crafted is impossible to imagine if     
one has not seen the Tower with his own eyes, yet the color of the glass     
is uneven; it is almost black in some places with traces of metallic     
colors, in others, the color is more chromatic. In most, however, it is     
perfectly clear, or almost perfectly clear. From the outside, it is mostly     
black.     
     
The inhabitants of the Glass Tower may have been many. Legends abound as to     
who they were, or may have been. Some would argue that they were a band     
of thieves who used it as a hideout or a clan of invading barbarians     
hiding from the combat in Kost. It is known for a fact, however, that the     
inhabitants were not magicians. The Scions of Knowledge, upon their     
emergence, seized the Tower with little trouble on the first day of the      
year 1200 AB. Two archmagi of the conclave arrived at the Tower's barred      
gates to destroy those who wereinside in order to take the Tower as their      
own. When the gates buckled to a mighty spell, the inside of the Tower was      
revealed, yet not a soul dwelled within. There are two rumors as to what     
may have happened to the former inhabitants. One, being more mundane and      
less popular amongst the common people, is that they heard word of powerful     
magi coming to kill them and fled. The second and more awe-inspiring rumor      
is that the Tower itself actually "ate" them once the Scions arrived, being      
that the mages were somehow destined to be there.     
     
The History of the Glass Tower is an enigmatic one. Every answer raises     
another question, and it will be some time until anything of real     
substance will be known, and even that much is not certain. It is certain     
however, that I will not be alive -- at least in this incarnation, to know     
it.     
~
